  "footnotes": [
    "La Tène culture (c.450–50 BCE): named after a site on Lake Neuchâtel in Switzerland, this is the defining archaeological culture of the later Celtic/Iron Age; La Tène art and metalwork spread across Europe from Iberia to Anatolia; the Helvetii who inhabited the Swiss Plateau were among the most powerful Celtic tribes",
    "Rütlischwur and the Old Swiss Confederacy (1291): according to tradition, representatives of Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden swore a mutual defense pact on the Rütli meadow; the Confederacy gradually expanded by defeating Habsburg armies at Morgarten (1315), Sempach (1386), and Näfels (1388); Swiss independence was a direct rejection of Habsburg authority",
    "Habsburg rise (1278–): Rudolf I of Habsburg seized Austria from Ottokar II of Bohemia at the Battle on the Marchfeld (1278); from this base, the Habsburgs built the most enduring European dynasty, eventually ruling Austria, Hungary, Bohemia, the Low Countries, Spain, and vast colonial territories — all from a family whose original castle stood in Swiss Aargau",
    "Swiss Reformation: Huldrych Zwingli's reforms in Zürich (1523) and John Calvin's theocratic Geneva (1541) made Switzerland a cradle of Reformed Protestantism; the confessional split between Catholic and Protestant cantons shaped Swiss politics for centuries and was only resolved by the Sonderbund War of 1847",
    "Peace of Westphalia (1648): the treaties ending the Thirty Years' War formally recognized Swiss independence from the Holy Roman Empire, confirming a de facto situation that had existed since the Swabian War of 1499; Switzerland's neutrality tradition dates from this era",
    "Anschluss (1938): Hitler's annexation of Austria into Nazi Germany was met with enthusiastic popular support in many quarters; Austria was treated as a German province ('Ostmark') until 1945; the post-war Moscow Declaration (1943) called Austria 'the first free country to fall victim to Hitlerite aggression', establishing the framework for Austrian sovereignty",
    "Austrian neutrality (1955): the Austrian State Treaty restored full sovereignty on the condition of permanent neutrality (modeled partly on Swiss neutrality); unlike Switzerland's centuries-old tradition, Austrian neutrality was a Cold War compromise — yet it became a core national identity, enabling Vienna to host major international organizations"
  ]
}
